    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about an escrow account for the closing and i'm kinda confused. what exactly is escrow and why do i need it for the house purchase?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow is a secure, neutral third-party account where funds and documents are held until the conditions of a real estate transaction are met. It's a bit like a safe haven for your money and paperwork, ensuring that both you and the seller can be confident that the deal will go through as agreed. The escrow account is managed by an escrow agent, who holds the funds until all the terms of the purchase are fulfilled, such as the home inspection, loan approval, and the signing of the final paperwork. This way, both parties can be assured that the deal won't fall through at the last minute. It's a way to keep things fair and square, preventing either side from trying to back out of the deal after everything is signed. So, in essence, the escrow account is like a trusty, impartial guardian of your house purchase, ensuring that everything goes according to plan.",
